member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.UpdateMask
member.summary: Reads diagnostics mask from the registry and recomputes cache while client is in use and the DiagnosticsManager changes the mask values.
member.remarks:
While client is in use and the DiagnosticsManager changes the mask values the client cache will not have the changed mask values. To get the changed mask values the client must be re-invoked or the user operation re-initiated to either call UpdateMask or re-create the GTDiagnostics object. Client should call UpdateMask infrequently, but they can call it more than once.
If an object has a relatively short life, there is generally no need to call UpdateMask. Objects with a longer life, such as long-running commands, should choose appropriate places to call UpdateMask. Some suggestions for places to call UpdateMask:
• In a command’s Activate method.
• In the Click event handler of a command or other event-handling object.

member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.LogEnter(System.String)
member.summary: Logs entering to a procedure. This message is logged as the Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagCat.EE category.
member.remarks:
A caller calls this method at the start of a procedure to log entering into a procedure. The caller must call LogExit when the procedure terminates (even if it terminates with an exception).
The message is logged in the following format:
<Date>|<Time>|<PID>|<TID>|[<InstanceID>]|<FileName>|<ProcedureName>|<SubsystemDescription>|Enter/exit|Entering
member.param: Specifies the procedure name that is logging the message.

member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.LogExit(System.String)
member.summary: Logs exiting from a procedure. This message is logged as the Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagCat.EE category.
member.remarks:
A caller calls this method at the end of a procedure to log exiting from a procedure. If LogEnter was called, then the caller must call LogExit when the procedure terminates (even if it terminates with an exception).
The message is logged in the following format:
<Date>|<Time>|<PID>|<TID>|[<InstanceID>]|<FileName>|<ProcedureName>|<SubsystemDescription>|Enter/exit|Exiting
member.param: Specifies the procedure name that is logging the message.

member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.Pause
member.summary: Temporarily stops diagnostic logging. No further diagnostics will be logged until Resume is called. No indication of the pause is logged. Pause and Resume calls should always be paired, but the pairs can be nested. Diagnostics are suspended until the outermost Resume is called.
member.remarks: For internal use only.

member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.Resume
member.summary: Restarts temporarily stopped diagnostic logging.
member.remarks: For internal use only.

member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.UserPause
member.summary: Temporarily stops diagnostic logging. The pause in diagnostics is logged, but no other diagnostics will be logged until UserResume is called.
member.remarks: For internal use only.

member.name: M:Intergraph.GTechnology.Diagnostics.GTDiagnostics.UserResume
member.summary: Restarts temporarily stopped diagnostic logging. The resumption is logged in the diagnostic log. Note that, unlike Pause and Resume, UserPause and UserResume need not occur in pairs and should not be nested. UserResume resumes paused logging, regardless of how many times UserPause has been called.
member.remarks: For internal use only.
